\begin_layout Problem
Calculate the arc length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

.
 I.e.
 calculate the distance one would have to travel along the circle to get
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
The arc length of the whole circle (i.e.
 the circumference) is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi r$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to a sector with central angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 The arc length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 corresponds to angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 representing 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\theta}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 of the total radians of the circle.
 Setting up the proportion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{2\pi r}{2\pi} & =\frac{L}{\theta}\\
r\theta & =L
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Equivalently, we might observe that if the whole circle has arc length 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi r$
\end_inset

, and the sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\theta}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 of the circle, then the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\theta}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 of the perimeter of the whole circle.
 Thus we compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\pi r\cdot\frac{\theta}{2\pi}=r\theta=L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Calculate the area of sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:area-of-sector"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
The full circle has area 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi r^{2}$
\end_inset

 and corresponds to a sector with central angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Our sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

 has central angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and unknown area 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Setting up the proportion we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\pi r^{2}}{2\pi} & =\frac{x}{\theta}\\
\frac{\theta r^{2}}{2} & =x\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Equivalently, we might observe that if the whole disk has area 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi r^{2}$
\end_inset

, and the sector represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\theta}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 of the disk, then its area is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\theta}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 of the area of the whole disk.
 Thus we compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x= & \pi r^{2}\cdot\frac{\theta}{2\pi}\\
= & \frac{\theta r^{2}}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

