\begin_layout Solution*
Using our answer to problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob:area-of-sector"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we know the area of sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we subtract the area of the triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle AOB$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{\downslice}AOB$
\end_inset

, we obtain the area of 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph$
\end_inset

.
 By converting to polar coordinates, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle AOB$
\end_inset

 has length 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and height 
\begin_inset Formula $r\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the area of 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle AOB$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{r^{2}\sin\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A(\aleph) & =\frac{r^{2}\theta}{2}-\frac{r^{2}\sin\theta}{2}\\
 & =\frac{r^{2}}{2}\left(\theta-\sin\theta\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


