\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Use elementary geometry to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|AB\right|=r$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|AB\right|=r$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|OB\right|=\left|OA\right|=r$
\end_inset

, all three sides of the triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle OAB$
\end_inset

 are equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, that is to say 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle OAB$
\end_inset

 is an equilateral triangle.
 By applying the isosceles triangle theorem twice, we can show that an equilater
al triangle must also be equiangular (i.e.
 have 3 equal angles).
 Thus all three interior angles of 
\begin_inset Formula $\triangle OAB$
\end_inset

 are equal.
 Since the angles of a triangle sum to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, each angle must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 So we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|AB\right|=r$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

