\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:slope-intercept-to-polar"

\end_inset

Given an arbitrary line in slope-intercept form 
\begin_inset Formula $y=mx+b$
\end_inset

, re-express the equation in polar coordinates with 
\begin_inset Formula $r=f\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Changing to polar, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y & =r\sin\theta\\
x & =r\cos\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y & =mx+b\\
r\sin\theta & =mr\cos\theta+b\\
r\sin\theta-mr\cos\theta & =b\\
r\left(\sin\theta-m\cos\theta\right) & =b\\
r & =\frac{b}{\sin\theta-m\cos\theta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:slope-to-polar"

\end_inset

Find the slope of the line through 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{AB}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
The slope 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{AB}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
m & =\frac{r\sin\theta-0}{r\cos\theta-r}\\
 & =\frac{r\sin\theta}{r\left(\cos\theta-1\right)}\\
 & =\frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta-1}\\
 & \overset{\gamma}{=}\frac{-1}{\tan\frac{\theta}{2}}\\
 & \overset{\delta}{=}-\cot\frac{\theta}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 follows from the half-angle formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tan\frac{\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cot$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Find the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 intercept of the line through 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{AB}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
To find the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-intercept of the line with slope 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-\cot\frac{\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

 passing through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,0\right)$
\end_inset

, we use the result of problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob:slope-intercept-to-polar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob:slope-to-polar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{b}{\sin\theta-m\cos\theta} & =r\\
b & =r\left(\sin\theta-m\cos\theta\right)\\
 & =r\left(\sin\theta+\cot\frac{\theta}{2}\cos\theta\right)\\
 & =r\left(\sin\theta+\frac{\sin\theta}{1-\cos\theta}\cos\theta\right)\\
 & =r\sin\theta\left(1+\frac{\cos\theta}{1-\cos\theta}\right)\\
 & \overset{\alpha}{=}r\sin\theta\left(\frac{1-\cos\theta}{1-\cos\theta}+\frac{\cos\theta}{1-\cos\theta}\right)\\
 & =r\sin\theta\left(\frac{1-\cos\theta+\cos\theta}{1-\cos\theta}\right)\\
 & =r\frac{\sin\theta}{1-\cos\theta}\\
 & =r\cot\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that in to obtain equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, we multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-\cos\theta}{1-\cos\theta}$
\end_inset

 to convert to a common denominator.
 
\end_layout

