\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Several parts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Recall point-slope form is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y-y_{1}=m\left(x-x_{1}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We identify for the intercept as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y-y_{1} & =m\left(x-x_{1}\right)\\
y & =mx-mx_{1}+y_{1}\\
y-mx & =-mx_{1}+y_{1}\\
 & =b
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b=-mx_{1}+y_{1}$
\end_inset

, using the result from problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob:slope-to-polar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

that 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-\cot\frac{\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

 and that the line passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)=\left(r,0\right)$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b & =-mx_{1}+y_{1}\\
 & =\cot\frac{\theta}{2}r
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To convert the point slope form of a line to polar form, we make the usual
 substitutions.
 One wrinkle is that we must use notation that distinguishes the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)=\left(r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 from the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x=r\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=r\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},y_{1}\right)=\left(r'\cos\theta',r''\sin\theta''\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\sin\theta-r'\sin\theta'=m\left(r\cos\theta-r''\cos\theta''\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We simply plug in for 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r'\cos\theta',r''\sin\theta''\right)$
\end_inset

 to the previous equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r\sin\theta-r'\sin\theta' & =m\left(r\cos\theta-r''\cos\theta''\right)\\
r\sin\theta-0 & =-\cot\frac{\theta'}{2}\left(r\cos\theta-r''\right)\\
r\sin\theta & =-\cot\frac{\theta'}{2}\left(r\cos\theta-r''\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob:slope-intercept-to-polar"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we know the polar form of a line in slope intercept form is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\frac{b}{\sin\theta-m\cos\theta}
\]

\end_inset

We also previously showed that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\cot\frac{\theta}{2}r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-\cot\frac{\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\frac{b}{\sin\theta-m\cos\theta}=\frac{\cot\frac{\theta}{2}r}{\sin\theta+\cot\frac{\theta}{2}\cos\theta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\cot\frac{\theta}{2}=\frac{\pi}{6}=\sqrt{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2$
\end_inset

, we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\frac{\cot\frac{\theta}{2}r}{\sin\theta+\cot\frac{\theta}{2}\cos\theta}=\frac{\sqrt{3}\cdot2}{\sin\theta+\sqrt{3}\cos\theta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\cot\frac{\theta}{2}r$
\end_inset

 is the intercept and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-\cot\frac{\theta}{2}$
\end_inset

 is the slope, when 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b=\sqrt{3}\cdot2,\hfill m=\sqrt{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In this problem, we found that the intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 was equal to the slope 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 multiplied by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $-r$
\end_inset

.
 That is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
m & =-\cot\frac{\theta}{2}\\
-mr & =\cot\frac{\theta}{2}r\\
 & =b
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we conjecture that it is always true that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=-mr$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

